I like Yoda conditions not only because it protects against the missing &quot;=&quot;, but also because often the constant is the shorter side, so reading<p><pre><code>    if (42 == some_long_expression_here)
    {
        ...
    }
</code></pre>
It is immediately clear that the rest of the line after the two equals signs must be an expression because the curly brace in the beginning of the next line.  So folks don&#x27;t have to bother that much about counting parens.

More importantly, they make it possible to have not-ugly documents (commas where they belong, after the clause they extend) work well with version control and merging.<p><pre><code>    -   &quot;blah&quot;
    +   &quot;blah&quot;,
    +   &quot;blorp&quot;
</code></pre>
is far uglier than any trailing comma ever has been.
